YENAGOA – An impounded crude oil vessel marked MTTIS IV and 22 crew members arrested onboard have been handed over to the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC) by the Nigerian Navy in Bayelsa State. The Commander, Nigerian Navy Ship (NNS) Soroh, Commodore Patrick Effah, handed over the vessel and the suspected oil thieves to the EFCC at Brass in the Brass Local Government Area of the state on Saturday. Effah said the vessel was loaded with 700, 000 litres of illegally sourced crude oil when it was seized alongside the 22 crew members on December 6, 2021 in the Akassa River. Police Nab 35 Year old Theft In Yobe Binniyat: 64 Days In Custody Without Bail, HURIWA Raises The… He said, “We have established the fact that the vessel and her crew are complicit in crime that borders on economic sabotage. “As a result of that, we are here to officially hand over the vessel and her crew to EFCC to carry out further investigations and prosecute the offenders for economic crime.” The NNS Soroh commander explained that the navy had the mandate to apprehend any ship believed to be carrying out illegalities in the Nigerian maritime domain. Effah said the navy does not have prosecutorial powers but have, by law, the obligation to hand over seized vessels and arrested crude oil thieves to the anti-graft agency for further investigation and prosecution. An Assistant Superintendent of the EFCC, Anthony Mark, who led a team from the Port Harcourt Zonal Office, while receiving the vessel and the suspects, said the commission would probe the incident thoroughly. POLL He said, “We will carry out thorough investigation with a view to determining the level of involvement, content of the vessel and prosecution of those involved.”